WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
MANILA OFFICIAL ESCAPES BOMBING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MANILA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Philippine justice secretary narrowly escaped a bomb attack on his home 
early today. 
</P>
<P>
Police said unidentified men hurled four bombs from a car at Franklin Drilon's 
home in the fashionable Manila district of Greenhills, damaging his two-story 
house and five other homes nearby and slightly injuring a neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
Drilon and his family escaped unhurt. 
</P>
<P>
"They were aimed at me because some of the bombs exploded just below the 
bedroom where I was sleeping," Drilon said in a radio interview. "Perhaps this 
is a message for me to go slow on the people we are investigating. I don't know 
who sent this message because we are investigating so many people." 
</P>
<P>
Drilon is in charge of prosecuting rebel soldiers linked to last December's 
sixth and most serious army coup attempt against President Corazon Aquino. 
</P>
</TEXT>
